In Django, URL routing is the process of directing incoming browser requests (URLs) to the appropriate view function. It‚Äôs like a traffic cop directing which function should respond when someone visits a certain URL on your site.


üõ†Ô∏è Project Plan
Project Name: mydjango_project
App Name: pages
Goal: Show a homepage with ‚ÄúWelcome to My Django Page!‚Äù using views & templates.

python -m django startproject core
So now that you‚Äôre in:

C:\Users\K\Documents\coding\python\mydjango_project
If you want to create a project named core, run:

python -m django startproject core .
üî∏ The . means: create the project in the current directory ‚Äî no extra folders.

‚úÖ Then continue like this:
1. Create the app
python manage.py startapp pages
2. Add 'pages' to core/settings.py ‚Üí INSTALLED_APPS
Open with:

notepad core/settings.py
Find:

INSTALLED_APPS = [
    ...
]
Change to:

INSTALLED_APPS = [
    'pages',
    'django.contrib.admin',
    'django.contrib.auth',
    ...
]
3. In pages/views.py, write:
from django.http import HttpResponse
def home(request):
    return HttpResponse("Welcome to the core homepage!")
4. Create pages/urls.py
notepad pages/urls.py
Paste this:

from django.urls import path
from . import views
urlpatterns = [
    path('', views.home, name='home'),
]
5. Connect app URLs in core/urls.py
Open:

notepad core/urls.py
Replace with:

from django.contrib import admin
from django.urls import path, include
urlpatterns = [
    path('admin/', admin.site.urls),
    path('', include('pages.urls')),
]
6. Run the server
python manage.py runserver
Then open http://127.0.0.1:8000 to see your message!
